default defaulta different section of Long Causeway. The arrow points at the same rock each time.  Again, it can be seen how the surface is being worn away and rocks that should form the foundation of the track are being exposed – in this case, the rock that is arrowed has moved from being reasonably buried in 2004 to being fully exposed now.  It can also be seen that a track which in 2004 was quite easily passable for walkers, riders and cyclists has now been turned into very difficult terrain:
default              default              default2004default              default              default2012default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default3. defaultI
defaultn these 2 photos it can be seen how significantly the surface is being worn away and also how the track is being widened as vehicles go off the track.  It can also be seen that water running in ruts created by the vehicles is eroding a track that in 2004 was quite easily passable for walkers, riders and cyclists.  Also note the steep drop to the left of this narrow track, making it difficult and even dangerous for walkers, riders and cyclists to avoid motorised vehicles as they pass:
